It looks like you want to integrate form handling with react-hook-form and authentication functionality into your login page component. Let's go step by step.

First, make sure you've installed react-hook-form, react-router-dom, and any other necessary dependencies. Then, implement the form handling and authentication logic into your LoginPage component.

Here's how you can integrate the provided imports and logic into your LoginPage component:

jsx
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';
import { useAuth } from '../controller/AuthContext.jsx';
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

export function LoginPage() {
    const { register, handleSubmit } = useForm();
    const { signin, isAuthenticated } = useAuth();
    const navigate = useNavigate();

    useEffect(() => {
        if (isAuthenticated) navigate('/');
    }, [isAuthenticated]);

    const onSubmit = handleSubmit((data) => {
        signin(data);
    });

    return (
        <div className="flex min-h-full flex-1 flex-col justify-center px-6 py-12 lg:px-8">
            <div className="sm:mx-auto sm:w-full sm:max-w-sm">
                {/* Your logo and title */}
            </div>

            <div className="mt-10 sm:mx-auto sm:w-full sm:max-w-sm">
                <form className="space-y-6" onSubmit={onSubmit}>
                    <div>
                        {/* Email input */}
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        {/* Password input */}
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        {/* Submit button */}
                    </div>
                </form>

                <p className="mt-10 text-center text-sm text-gray-500">
                    Not a member?{' '}
                    <a href="#" className="font-semibold leading-6 text-indigo-600 hover:text-indigo-500">
                        Start a 14 day free trial
                    </a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    );
}

export default LoginPage;

Replace the placeholders in the code with the corresponding JSX elements from your original LoginPage component. Ensure that your useAuth hook and authentication logic are correctly implemented in the signin function.

With this setup, when a user submits the form, the handleSubmit function will call the signin function with the form data. If authentication is successful, the user will be redirected to the home page ('/'). Otherwise, they will remain on the login page.

    const { register, handleSubmit } = useForm();

                />
            </div>
